Contextual Price Movement 

102
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:31,280
When you analyze your chart, you can't 
just look at candles in isolation. 

103
00:09:31,280 --> 00:09:35,520
It's essential to understand 
the context in which they occur. 

104
00:09:35,520 --> 00:09:41,520
This context tells you whether the market is 
in an impulse phase, or a corrective phase.
  

105
00:09:41,520 --> 00:09:46,080
Let's start with impulse movements.
These are strong, directional moves  

106
00:09:46,080 --> 00:09:51,600
in the market, where prices trend 
sharply either upward or downward. 

107
00:09:51,600 --> 00:09:57,040
In technical terms, an impulse move is 
characterized by a series of candles  

108
00:09:57,040 --> 00:10:02,000
that move in the same direction, 
often with increasing momentum. 

109
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:07,360
This is usually accompanied by high trading 
volume, which signals strong interest  

110
00:10:07,360 --> 00:10:12,720
and participation in the market. 
 
Now, look at corrective movements. 

111
00:10:12,720 --> 00:10:17,360
These are periods where the market 
takes a breather, moving sideways  

112
00:10:17,360 --> 00:10:22,640
or slightly against the main trend.
The candles during a correction are  

113
00:10:22,640 --> 00:10:29,200
typically smaller, and the volume may 
decrease, indicating less participation. 

114
00:10:29,200 --> 00:10:33,600
Corrective phases can be seen as 
consolidation periods, where the  

115
00:10:33,600 --> 00:10:40,560
market digests previous gains or losses, 
before potentially resuming its trend.
 
  

116
00:10:40,560 --> 00:10:45,120
Understanding whether the market is 
in an impulse or corrective phase can  

117
00:10:45,120 --> 00:10:52,320
significantly influence your trading strategies.
Let's say you're observing an upward impulse move.  

118
00:10:52,320 --> 00:10:59,360
This might be a signal to enter long positions, 
aiming to profit from the strong upward trend. 

119
00:10:59,360 --> 00:11:05,440
In contrast, during a corrective phase, 
you might employ different tactics.
  

120
00:11:05,440 --> 00:11:12,640
You can also use support and resistance levels, to 
determine where these phases might begin or end. 

121
00:11:12,640 --> 00:11:19,200
An impulse move may break through a 
resistance level, signaling a strong trend. 

122
00:11:19,200 --> 00:11:23,520
A correction might occur as the 
price approaches a support level,  

123
00:11:23,520 --> 00:11:30,320
potentially reversing or pausing the trend.
 
 
Combine this with volume profile or footprint  

124
00:11:30,320 --> 00:11:35,360
charts. During an impulse phase, 
you often see a surge in volume,  

125
00:11:35,360 --> 00:11:41,200
confirming the strength of the trend.
In contrast, a decrease in volume during  

126
00:11:41,200 --> 00:11:48,000
a corrective phase, implies a lack of conviction 
in moving against the main trend, hinting that  

127
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:51,280
the correction may be temporary.
 
 
Liquidity Hunting Techniques 

128
00:11:51,280 --> 00:11:55,520
Markets often move to areas 
with concentrated liquidity. 

129
00:11:55,520 --> 00:12:01,920
When we talk about liquidity, we're referring 
to areas where concentrated orders exist. 

130
00:12:01,920 --> 00:12:06,000
These zones are like magnets 
that attract price movement. 

131
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:09,920
And institutional traders 
deliberately target these zones,  

132
00:12:09,920 --> 00:12:15,840
to trigger significant market movements.
 
Picture traders placing their stop-loss  

133
00:12:15,840 --> 00:12:22,400
orders clustered around similar price levels.
When price reaches these zones, it creates  

134
00:12:22,400 --> 00:12:29,600
a cascade of automatic buy or sell orders.
This sudden surge of orders can cause sharp,  

135
00:12:29,600 --> 00:12:34,400
dramatic price movements that 
catch many traders off guard.
  

136
00:12:34,400 --> 00:12:40,320
The process works like a strategic trap. 
Traders often place stop-loss orders at  

137
00:12:40,320 --> 00:12:46,080
predictable levels. Smart money traders 
recognize these patterns and deliberately  

138
00:12:46,080 --> 00:12:51,600
push price towards these zones.
When triggered, these stop-loss orders  

139
00:12:51,600 --> 00:12:57,680
generate what traders call "sell-side 
liquidity" or "buy-side liquidity".
  

140
00:12:57,680 --> 00:13:04,240
For instance, during a bullish market, traders 
might place stop-loss orders just below recent  

141
00:13:04,240 --> 00:13:10,560
low points. Big players can intentionally 
drive price down to trigger these stops,  

142
00:13:10,560 --> 00:13:16,480
creating a sudden influx of sell orders.
This allows them to enter buy positions  

143
00:13:16,480 --> 00:13:22,160
at more favorable prices. 
 
Liquidity pools are not random.  

144
00:13:22,160 --> 00:13:28,720
They're strategic zones where significant 
numbers of buy or sell orders get together. 

145
00:13:28,720 --> 00:13:35,440
These pools exist across different timeframes.
In your technical analysis, you must find and  

146
00:13:35,440 --> 00:13:40,560
analyze these pools, to identify 
potential trade opportunities.
  

147
00:13:40,560 --> 00:13:46,080
Validation of these liquidity zones 
happens through specific price movements. 

148
00:13:46,080 --> 00:13:52,000
When price violates a recent low, 
sell stops become market sell orders. 

149
00:13:52,000 --> 00:13:58,480
When price breaks above a recent high, buy 
stops transform into market buy orders. 

150
00:13:58,480 --> 00:14:04,240
This mechanism injects liquidity and often 
accompanies smart money positioning.
  

151
00:14:04,240 --> 00:14:09,440
Entry techniques for liquidity hunting 
require precision. When a market shows  

152
00:14:09,440 --> 00:14:16,080
bullish characteristics, you might place 
buy limit orders just below recent lows. 

153
00:14:16,080 --> 00:14:21,360
This strategy mimics how institutional 
traders would enter positions,  

154
00:14:21,360 --> 00:14:27,440
essentially "buying the sell stops".
The reverse holds true for bearish markets.  

155
00:14:27,440 --> 00:14:34,240
You can place sell limit orders just above 
recent highs, selling the accumulated buy stops. 

156
00:14:34,240 --> 00:14:38,560
This approach allows you to trade 
like institutional players, taking  

157
00:14:38,560 --> 00:14:45,280
advantage of predictable market behaviors.
 
Basically, you plan to enter in areas where  

158
00:14:45,280 --> 00:14:51,760
novice traders are placing their stops.
The truth is institutional traders often  

159
00:14:51,760 --> 00:14:58,560
create scenarios that manipulate our perceptions.
They might make the market appear bearish, when  

160
00:14:58,560 --> 00:15:04,400
they actually want to accumulate buy positions.
Or they might create a bullish appearance,  

161
00:15:04,400 --> 00:15:11,760
precisely when they aim to gather sell positions.
The goal is to trade in low-resistance conditions. 

162
00:15:11,760 --> 00:15:16,720
This means identifying paths with 
minimal obstacles to profitability. 
  

163
00:15:16,720 --> 00:15:22,000
Every time the market establishes a new 
range, mark the high and low points. 

164
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:28,560
Mark the internal and external range liquidity.
It's about thinking several steps ahead,  

165
00:15:28,560 --> 00:15:34,926
anticipating where institutional traders 
might want to generate order flow. 
  

166
00:15:34,926 --> 00:15:37,520
Market Sentiment Volume Divergence
Markets breathe through volume. Every  

167
00:15:37,520 --> 00:15:42,800
price movement tells a story, but 
volume reveals the true narrative. 

168
00:15:42,800 --> 00:15:48,560
When price rises but volume declines, 
it's like the market is losing steam. 

169
00:15:48,560 --> 00:15:52,560
Professional traders recognize 
this as a warning sign. 

170
00:15:52,560 --> 00:15:58,720
The market might look strong on the surface, 
but the underlying energy is fading.
  

171
00:15:58,720 --> 00:16:03,600
Volume divergence happens when price 
and trading volume don't align. 

172
00:16:03,600 --> 00:16:09,760
Picture a stock climbing higher, but the 
volume supporting that climb is decreasing. 

173
00:16:09,760 --> 00:16:17,040
This mismatch signals potential market weakness.
Traders call this a "volume divergence" - a  

174
00:16:17,040 --> 00:16:22,160
critical indicator of market health.
 
Think of volume as the fuel powering  

175
00:16:22,160 --> 00:16:28,160
price movement. A rising market needs 
strong volume to sustain its momentum. 

176
00:16:28,160 --> 00:16:34,160
When volume drops during an uptrend, it 
implies the move might be running out of steam. 

177
00:16:34,160 --> 00:16:39,280
Professional traders see this as 
traders losing interest or confidence.
  

178
00:16:39,920 --> 00:16:46,320
A strong uptrend should have increasing volume.
If volume fails to confirm price movement,  

179
00:16:46,320 --> 00:16:53,600
it indicates potential trend reversal. So look for 
these subtle signals to anticipate market shifts. 

180
00:16:53,600 --> 00:16:57,920
Institutional traders pay close 
attention to volume patterns. 

181
00:16:57,920 --> 00:17:03,360
They understand that volume tells a 
story beyond simple price movement. 
  

182
00:17:03,360 --> 00:17:09,920
When volume decreases during a price rise, it 
might also mean smart money is preparing to exit  

183
00:17:09,920 --> 00:17:17,520
their positions. This is a classic warning sign.
Consider a market climbing steadily. Normally,  

184
00:17:17,520 --> 00:17:23,680
you'd expect volume to increase as price 
moves higher. But if volume remains flat  

185
00:17:23,680 --> 00:17:31,040
or decreases, it suggests lack of conviction.
This is a potential sign of market exhaustion.
  

186
00:17:31,040 --> 00:17:36,880
I said it before: volume analysis goes 
beyond simple up and down movements. 

187
00:17:36,880 --> 00:17:42,080
It's about understanding market 
sentiment and trader participation. 

188
00:17:42,080 --> 00:17:48,160
A rising market with decreasing volume might 
indicate that fewer traders believe in the  

189
00:17:48,160 --> 00:17:53,840
current price direction. This could 
signal an impending trend reversal. 

190
00:17:53,840 --> 00:17:58,720
When volume fails to match price 
movement, it raises red flags. 
  

191
00:17:58,720 --> 00:18:04,240
So look for these volume nuances.
And understand that volume is more than just  

192
00:18:04,240 --> 00:18:11,040
numbers - it's a reflection of market sentiment.
A rising market with weak volume might look  

193
00:18:11,040 --> 00:18:15,760
strong on the surface, but it lacks 
the underlying support to continue. 

194
00:18:15,760 --> 00:18:21,760
And another point: market psychology 
becomes visible through volume analysis. 

195
00:18:21,760 --> 00:18:27,840
When traders lose confidence, volume 
drops. This silent signal often precedes  

196
00:18:27,840 --> 00:18:31,280
significant market movements. 
 
 
Dynamic Support/Resistance Evolution 

197
00:18:31,280 --> 00:18:36,000
A good technician understands that 
support and resistance are a dynamic  

198
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:42,720
