Support and resistance are not permanent  

207
00:19:28,240 --> 00:19:32,800
structures, they are constantly 
reshaped by market forces. 

208
00:19:32,800 --> 00:19:38,560
A zone where prices previously consolidated, 
becomes a critical psychological  

209
00:19:38,560 --> 00:19:45,920
battleground for future price action.
Consider how markets create these dynamic zones. 

210
00:19:45,920 --> 00:19:50,480
Traders accumulate positions, 
create buying and selling pressure,  

211
00:19:50,480 --> 00:19:56,240
and generate areas of price congestion.
These zones become critical transition  

212
00:19:56,240 --> 00:20:01,600
points, where market sentiment can 
potentially reverse or accelerate.
  

213
00:20:01,600 --> 00:20:07,440
Technical analysts recognize these 
zones as more than simple price levels. 

214
00:20:07,440 --> 00:20:14,000
They're psychological battlegrounds 
where buyer and seller intentions clash. 

215
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:20,960
When price breaks through these zones, the 
entire market landscape potentially transforms.
  

216
00:20:20,960 --> 00:20:27,280
The market's internal logic reveals itself through 
these dynamic support and resistance zones. 

217
00:20:27,280 --> 00:20:33,200
Again, previous support becomes future 
resistance when price breaks lower. 

218
00:20:33,200 --> 00:20:38,800
Traders who bought at those levels now 
become potential sellers, creating a  

219
00:20:38,800 --> 00:20:44,000
natural resistance ceiling.
 
And another point: zones that  

220
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:50,000
previously contained price can become 
launching points for future movement. 

221
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:54,960
Price congestion plays a huge 
role in how these zones evolve. 

222
00:20:54,960 --> 00:21:01,680
When price moves sideways for a while, it 
creates a zone where lots of orders pile up. 

223
00:21:01,680 --> 00:21:05,520
These congestion zones can last 
for different amounts of time.
  

224
00:21:05,520 --> 00:21:12,880
Again, instead of drawing multiple thin lines 
close together, view these areas as wider zones. 

225
00:21:12,880 --> 00:21:18,320
This gives a clearer picture of where 
real buying and selling pressure exists.
  

226
00:21:18,320 --> 00:21:23,200
The strength of these evolving 
zones depends on several factors. 

227
00:21:23,200 --> 00:21:30,320
First, how long did price spend there? Longer 
congestion periods create stronger zones. 

228
00:21:30,320 --> 00:21:37,440
Second, how recently was that zone tested? 
Fresh tests carry more weight than old ones. 

229
00:21:37,440 --> 00:21:43,520
Third, how dramatic was the move away 
from the zone? Big, fast moves show  

230
00:21:43,520 --> 00:21:46,800
stronger rejection of that level.
 
Contextual Indicator Filtering 

231
00:21:46,800 --> 00:21:53,120
Technical indicators work best as supporting 
tools, not as your main decision drivers. 

232
00:21:53,120 --> 00:21:59,440
They're like a compass - helpful for direction, 
but you still need to watch where you're walking. 

233
00:21:59,440 --> 00:22:04,720
Price remains the core truth in trading! 
 
Every technical indicator comes  

234
00:22:04,720 --> 00:22:09,120
from price calculations.
Moving averages, for example,  

235
00:22:09,120 --> 00:22:15,120
simply average prices over time.
Oscillators measure price momentum. 

236
00:22:15,120 --> 00:22:19,840
These tools can point out things you 
might miss on the price chart alone,  

237
00:22:19,840 --> 00:22:25,920
but they shouldn't override what price tells you.
That’s why setting up indicators needs  

238
00:22:25,920 --> 00:22:28,880
careful thought. 
 
Many traders make the  

239
00:22:28,880 --> 00:22:35,120
mistake of using random settings, without 
understanding why those numbers exist. 

240
00:22:35,120 --> 00:22:41,520
Each market has its own personality, what 
works for stocks might not work for currencies. 

241
00:22:41,520 --> 00:22:46,960
The key is to match your indicator 
settings to the market you're trading.
  

242
00:22:46,960 --> 00:22:51,280
Also, too many indicators on 
your chart create confusion. 

243
00:22:51,280 --> 00:22:54,000
If you really think you can’t trade without them,  

244
00:22:54,000 --> 00:22:59,440
pick a few that complement each other, and 
understand exactly what they tell you.
  

245
00:22:59,440 --> 00:23:04,000
Know this: markets change 
their behavior patterns often. 

246
00:23:04,000 --> 00:23:11,360
During some periods, they move in clear trends. 
Other times, they swing back and forth in ranges. 

247
00:23:11,360 --> 00:23:15,680
Your indicator settings need 
to adapt to these changes. 

248
00:23:15,680 --> 00:23:24,240
A 14-period RSI might work great in a trending 
market, but give false signals in a choppy one.
  

249
00:23:24,240 --> 00:23:28,880
This is probably the biggest problem 
in technical analysis: many traders  

250
00:23:28,880 --> 00:23:34,880
fall into the trap of indicator overload.
They stack multiple tools on their charts,  

251
00:23:34,880 --> 00:23:38,480
thinking more is better.
This usually leads to  

252
00:23:38,480 --> 00:23:43,520
confusion and missed trades. 
 
It’s best to keep your setup simple  

253
00:23:43,520 --> 00:23:48,080
and focused on price action.
Let indicators confirm what  

254
00:23:48,080 --> 00:23:52,400
price already shows you!
Focus on tools that help you  

255
00:23:52,400 --> 00:23:58,960
see the bigger picture, rather than those 
that give frequent but unreliable signals. 

256
00:23:58,960 --> 00:24:05,680
Good indicators help you understand what's 
happening with price, not replace price analysis.
  

257
00:24:05,680 --> 00:24:10,000
Also, switching between different 
indicators or constantly changing  

258
00:24:10,000 --> 00:24:15,760
settings usually hurts results.
Pick your tools carefully, understand them,  

259
00:24:15,760 --> 00:24:21,520
and stick with them long enough to see how 
they perform in different market conditions.
  

260
00:24:21,520 --> 00:24:27,520
The real power of indicators comes from 
how you combine them with price action. 

261
00:24:27,520 --> 00:24:34,400
For example, if price shows a potential reversal 
pattern, you might use an oscillator, to confirm  

262
00:24:34,400 --> 00:24:39,840
whether the market is shows a divergence.
The price pattern matters more than the  

263
00:24:39,840 --> 00:24:42,560
indicator reading.
 
Remember this:  

264
00:24:42,560 --> 00:24:48,960
indicators can point out potential trades, 
but price action must confirm these signals. 

265
00:24:48,960 --> 00:24:56,080
If an oscillator shows oversold conditions 
but price keeps making lower lows, trust the  

266
00:24:56,080 --> 00:24:59,600
price action, not the indicator!
 
Price Chart Strategic Insights 

267
00:24:59,600 --> 00:25:06,080
Alternative chart types like Renko, Range, or 
Tick charts, offer more refined perspectives. 

268
00:25:06,080 --> 00:25:11,920
These price charts show market data in 
different ways than standard time-based charts.
 

269
00:25:11,920 --> 00:25:16,880
Tick charts create new bars after 
a specific number of trades. 

270
00:25:16,880 --> 00:25:21,040
They show real trading activity 
rather than time periods. 

271
00:25:21,040 --> 00:25:27,440
Active trading periods show more bars, 
while quiet periods show fewer bars. 

272
00:25:27,440 --> 00:25:33,520
This reveals true market activity patterns 
that time-based charts might hide.
  

273
00:25:33,520 --> 00:25:41,600
Renko charts filter out minor price moves. They 
draw new boxes only when price moves a set amount.  

274
00:25:41,600 --> 00:25:47,040
This removes time from the equation 
and focuses on pure price movement. 

275
00:25:47,040 --> 00:25:54,560
Renko charts excel at showing strong trends and 
make support and resistance levels very clear.
  

276
00:25:54,560 --> 00:25:59,520
Range bars create new bars based 
on price movement, not time. 

277
00:25:59,520 --> 00:26:04,960
Each bar covers the same price range. 
This helps you see price momentum:  

278
00:26:04,960 --> 00:26:13,200
tight clusters of bars suggest consolidation, 
while spread-out bars show strong trends. 
  

279
00:26:13,200 --> 00:26:18,240
These price-based charts show true 
market activity, unlike time-based  

280
00:26:18,240 --> 00:26:24,080
charts which can mask some market moves.
A time chart creates new candles at set  

281
00:26:24,080 --> 00:26:30,000
intervals, whether there's trading action 
or not, missing key market dynamics.
  

282
00:26:30,000 --> 00:26:35,120
Think about trading during major 
news releases. On a time-based chart,  

283
00:26:35,120 --> 00:26:40,000
you see the same one-minute or 
five-minute candles forming steadily. 

284
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:45,600
But during high activity, those candles 
might contain thousands of trades,  

285
00:26:45,600 --> 00:26:53,200
while during quiet periods, they might show just a 
few trades. This hides the real market intensity.
  

286
00:26:53,200 --> 00:26:59,680
Take the New York session opening as an example. 
On a tick chart, which creates new candles  

287
00:26:59,680 --> 00:27:07,200
after a specific number of trades, you might see 
candles forming in seconds during active periods. 

288
00:27:07,200 --> 00:27:14,080
The same tick chart, during quiet Asian trading, 
might take several minutes to form each candle. 

289
00:27:14,080 --> 00:27:19,200
This visual difference shows you exactly 
when the market gets busy or quiet.
  

290
00:27:19,200 --> 00:27:23,040
The reality is that time charts 
may give you a fixed view. 

291
00:27:23,040 --> 00:27:30,480
Price-based charts, like tick charts, adjust 
their speed based on actual trading activity. 

292
00:27:30,480 --> 00:27:35,600
This helps you spot market energy and 
potential moves before they happen.
  

293
00:27:35,600 --> 00:27:39,040
Tick charts reveal the true 
heartbeat of the market. 

294
00:27:39,040 --> 00:27:44,240
They show you 'inside' market 
activity that time-based charts miss. 

295
00:27:44,240 --> 00:27:50,160
Professional traders often prefer tick charts 
because they display real trading flow,  

296
00:27:50,160 --> 00:27:55,200
rather than arbitrary time divisions.
 
That’s the main advantage: price  

297
00:27:55,200 --> 00:28:02,160
charts focus on actual market movement. 
During slow periods, fewer candles form. 

298
00:28:02,160 --> 00:28:07,680
During active times, more candles appear.
This natural rhythm helps you spot  

299
00:28:07,680 --> 00:28:11,600
changes in market behavior.
 
While time charts show what  

300
00:28:11,600 --> 00:28:18,160
happened during fixed periods, price charts 
show what happened during actual market moves. 

301
00:28:18,160 --> 00:28:23,600
This difference matters because markets 
don't move in neat time packages - they  

302
00:28:23,600 --> 00:28:31,200
move based on trading activity and price action.
 
Price charts work especially well for day trading. 

303
00:28:31,200 --> 00:28:36,240
They help measure the emotional intensity 
of market participants - something that  

304
00:28:36,240 --> 00:28:41,680
time-based charts often fail to show.
